Unless you have a very good reason, you should definitely pick option your boss gave you. One alternative is this:

    void do_my_func1(int flag)
    {
       if (flag)
       {
          ..do the processing for this function
       }
    }

What is best depends on the situation and cannot be determined in a general example like this.

Avoid globals when you can. There are some cases where they are good, but being lazy is not one of them. ;)

If there are very many flags, pack them into an array or a struct.

In this case boss is right.
In your code there will always be a function call. Which is useless if flag is not set.
Checking condition takes much less time than calling a function. Calling a function requires lot of processing. ([link][1])
It&#39;s much easier to evaluate a condition.
In modern compiler branch prediction is more accurate and saves a lot of time by eliminating a function call.
You can make a small demo to verify this:
`

    main()
    {
       int n=INTMAX;
       int m=INTMAX;
       struct timeval start, stop;
       double msecs = 0;

       gettimeofday(&amp;start, NULL);
       for(;n&gt;0;n--){
           for(;m&gt;0;m--){  
               if (flag)
               {
                  do_my_func1();
               }
               ...
            }
        }
       gettimeofday(&amp;stop, NULL);
       msecs = (double)(stop.tv_usec - start.tv_usec) / 1000.0f + (double)(stop.tv_sec - start.tv_sec)*1000.0f ;
       printf(&quot;time taken %f\n&quot;,msecs);
    }
    
    void do_my_func1()
    {
       ..do the processing for this function
    }`

v/s your version and record the time.

  [1]: https://qr.ae/TWsUds

